White House Press Secretary Robert Gibbs held a press briefing on March 11, 2009. During the briefing, he discussed President Obama's stance on earmarks and the need for reform. Gibbs also addressed questions about the President's meeting with the Chinese Foreign Minister and the situation in Mexico. He mentioned that the President believes the economic crisis is as challenging as any problem the country has faced in 50 or 60 years. Additionally, Gibbs commented on the D.C. scholarship program and the controversy surrounding Adolfo Carrion. He also touched on the situation in Darfur and the possible appointment of an envoy for closing Guantanamo Bay. Gibbs concluded by providing a brief overview of the President's upcoming schedule.